I’m probably the least likely person you would think is an advocate of environmental policies.

Or maybe you do see me as one. Who knows. But I don’t wear hemp clothing (I think cotton is king, really and technical fabrics keep me cool while running), sandals, tie-dye, or anything that can be considered hippie-ish.

But I think that concept of being an environment advocate and being a dirty hippie (sorry my dirty hippie friends) has slowly been eradicated. Thank goodness.

So what do I do to help out my “carbon footprint” (I really hate that term and I wish they would stop using it. It really is a garish, idiotic soundbite) So let me try again, what do I do to lessen my impact on our ecosystem?

I started reading the collected Cornelius Quartet by Michael Moorcock. According to the back cover, and Wikipedia, the character seems to have had plenty of influence on subsequent writers. And I can’t walk around the internet without stepping on someone that raves about Moorcock’s writing.

So am I missing something? The writing is clunky and at times just painful to read. Moorcock’s descriptions border on laundry lists, there is no suspense during suspenseful scenes, the dialogue stinks, and I think at one point he used the word “together” three times in one sentence.

As for the influence of Cornelius on future authors and genres, I can’t speak to since I don’t know much about him as a character.

But I am really starting to think that Moorcock might be one of those authors whose reputation is blown out of proportion by his fans.

Well right now Marvel has a Green Hulk. a Red Hulk, a Grey Hulk, a Blue Hulk like creature, and I suspect if they could pull it off we would have several other Hulk colors.

Hulk: Green Hulk/Red Hulk is the hardcover collection of the story that ran through the Hulk comic last year. We have a new Hulk introduced and he is Red and we have no background on him except that he seems intelligent, psychopathic, and gets hot when he gets mad.

Oh and he seems to be something that Dr. Samson and Gen Ross put together to kill Banner’s Green Hulk.

This isn’t a great story, but it is fun and what Hulk comics should be: Huge fights with major amounts of property damage.

This last long run wasn’t any different. Just a little worse actually.

RW Racing News: A Brief Chat With Amy Palmiero-Winters

Amy Palmiero-Winters, 37, finished first, ahead of all the women AND men, at the Run to the Future 24-Hour race in Glendale, Arizona on December 31 and January 1 and made the U.S. team for the 2010 World 24-Hour Run Championship in Brive, France, in May. She covered 130.04 miles in Glendale, winning by 14 miles; she needed 129.6 to qualify for the Worlds

Oh, and the one thing about Amy that makes it even more embarrassing for all of us. . .
